It is officially logged. I have 2.3 flight hours ^_^
#TeaganAir
If I had to describe what it's like to fly in a small airplane, I would say it's a mix of a motorcycle/quadruple and a boat at 4,000 feet in the air.
On the ground, you're very fast right away. Everything is a bit unstable on the ground, so that's why it's like a motorcycle/quadruple.
And if you didn't know: You control a plane on the ground with your feet, not with the steering stick. Rudder pedals and brakes. It's not a car.
In the air, it's shaky and you kind of swim. It feels like being in a boat on water. You can steer it, but sometimes a wave comes and throws you off balance, so you basically have to get used to the sea motion, just in the air.
One more random detail:
Flying is physically exhausting. Today, my back and legs hurt *a lot*, as if I had been to the gym.
This isn't like a Sunday drive in the car. To me, it's more of a sport than a leisurely ride.
A beautiful Saturday, my loves. Welcome at 4,000 feet.
Tomorrow I'll go up again. Then we will practice streamer release and slow flying.
Today the weather was turbulent but it was lots of fun. We practiced slow flying and streamer release. Once we had a ground speed of only 16 mph while flying at 65 mph.
It was a nice clear day, a bit chilly higher up, but still beautiful.
